            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this India salary calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is designed to bridge the gap between the CTC number
                on your offer letter and the actual in-hand salary that hits
                your bank account every month. It follows a typical Indian
                corporate salary structure and applies common statutory
                deductions like PF, ESI, professional tax and income tax (TDS).
              </p>

              <h3>1. From CTC to fixed salary</h3>
              <p>We first split your CTC into:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Fixed CTC</strong> – the part paid every month (basic
                  + HRA + allowances).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Variable / bonus</strong> – annual bonus or
                  performance pay (spread evenly across 12 months for
                  estimation).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Employer contributions</strong> – employer PF, ESI and
                  gratuity, which increase CTC but are not fully part of your
                  in-hand salary.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Step 1 – Split CTC:</strong></p>
                <p>\(\text{Bonus} = \text{CTC} \times \text{Bonus%}\)</p>
                <p>\(\text{Provisional Fixed} = \text{CTC} - \text{Bonus}\)</p>
                <p>
                  We then back-calculate employer PF, ESI and gratuity from this
                  provisional fixed amount to arrive at:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Fixed Cash} \approx \text{Provisional Fixed} -
                  \text{Employer PF} - \text{Employer ESI} - \text{Gratuity}\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Building your monthly salary structure</h3>
              <p>
                From the fixed cash component we construct a standard salary
                structure:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Basic salary</strong> = Fixed cash × Basic% (default
                  40%).
                </li>
                <li><strong>HRA</strong> = Basic × HRA% (default 40%).</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Other allowances</strong> = Fixed cash − Basic − HRA.
                </li>
                <li><strong>Monthly bonus</strong> = Annual bonus ÷ 12.</li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Monthly earnings:</strong></p>
                <p>\(\text{Basic}_{m} = \dfrac{\text{Basic}}{12}\)</p>
                <p>\(\text{HRA}_{m} = \dfrac{\text{HRA}}{12}\)</p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Allowances}_{m} = \dfrac{\text{Other
                  Allowances}}{12}\)
                </p>
                <p>\(\text{Bonus}_{m} = \dfrac{\text{Bonus}}{12}\)</p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Gross}_{m} = \text{Basic}_{m} + \text{HRA}_{m} +
                  \text{Allowances}_{m} + \text{Bonus}_{m}\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Statutory deductions: PF, ESI, professional tax</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Employee PF</strong> = PF% × basic (default 12%), with
                  an optional wage ceiling of ₹15,000 basic per month.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Employer PF</strong> = same rate on the same base,
                  counted inside CTC.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>ESI</strong> (if enabled and gross ≤ threshold) – we
                  use 0.75% employee and 3.25% employer on gross as a typical
                  assumption.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Professional Tax (PT)</strong> – applied as a flat
                  monthly amount based on the state you choose and your gross
                  slab.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Employee PF (monthly):</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{PF base}_{m} = \min(\text{Basic}_{m}, 15{,}000)\) if
                  ceiling is enabled
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{PF}_{m} = \text{PF base}_{m} \times
                  \dfrac{\text{PF%}}{100}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Employee ESI (monthly):</strong> \(\text{ESI}_{m} =
                  \text{Gross}_{m} \times 0.75\%\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Income tax (TDS) under old vs new regime</h3>
              <p>
                We estimate your annual taxable income and then apply the chosen
                regime’s slab rates. For simplicity we assume:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Standard deduction of ₹50,000 for both regimes.</li>
                <li>
                  No additional deductions (like 80C, 80D, HRA exemption) – you
                  can mentally adjust for your own investments.
                </li>
                <li>Rebate under section 87A is applied where applicable.</li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Taxable income:</strong></p>
                <p>\(\text{Taxable} = \text{Annual Gross} - 50{,}000\)</p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Approx. annual tax</strong> = slab-wise tax (old or
                  new) + 4% health &amp; education cess − rebate (if eligible).
                </p>
                <p><strong>Monthly TDS</strong> ≈ Annual tax ÷ 12</p>
              </div>

              <h3>5. Net salary (in-hand) formula</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Monthly net salary:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Net}_{m} = \text{Gross}_{m} - \text{Employee PF}_{m} -
                  \text{Employee ESI}_{m} - \text{PT}_{m} - \text{TDS}_{m}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Annual net salary:</strong> \(\text{Net}_{y} =
                  \text{Net}_{m} \times 12\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Understanding your Indian payslip: key components</h2>
              <h3>Common earnings heads</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Basic Pay</strong> – core of your salary; drives PF,
                  gratuity and many allowances.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>HRA (House Rent Allowance)</strong> – tax-efficient if
                  you live in rented accommodation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Special / Flexi / Other Allowances</strong> – balance
                  component; usually fully taxable.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Bonus / Performance Pay</strong> – may be monthly,
                  quarterly or annual; often variable.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Common deduction heads</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>PF (Employee)</strong> – 12% of basic (typically),
                  locked in EPF/VPF.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>ESI (Employee)</strong> – for eligible salaries;
                  provides medical and social security benefits.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Professional Tax</strong> – small state-level tax
                  deducted monthly.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>TDS (Tax Deducted at Source)</strong> – income tax
                  withheld by employer and deposited with the government.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Worked example: CTC ₹12,00,000</h2>
              <p>Assume:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>CTC = ₹12,00,000</li>
                <li>Bonus = 10% of CTC (₹1,20,000)</li>
                <li>Basic = 40% of fixed, HRA = 40% of basic</li>
                <li>PF = 12% on basic with wage ceiling</li>
                <li>New tax regime, Karnataka PT</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator will show an approximate monthly gross,
                deductions and net. You can tweak the sliders to match your
                actual offer letter and see how your in-hand changes.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ: Net salary vs CTC in India</h2>

              <h3>Is employer PF part of my salary?</h3>
              <p>
                Employer PF is part of your CTC but not part of your monthly
                in-hand salary. It goes directly into your EPF account and can
                be withdrawn or transferred as per EPF rules.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Why is my in-hand salary lower than friends with similar CTC?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Two offers with the same CTC can have very different take-home
                because of:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Different basic/HRA/allowance splits.</li>
                <li>PF on full basic vs capped at ₹15,000.</li>
                <li>Higher variable/bonus component.</li>
                <li>Location-specific professional tax.</li>
                <li>Different tax-saving investments and declarations.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>How can I increase my take-home salary?</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Optimize your tax regime choice (old vs new).</li>
                <li>
                  Use 80C, 80D and other deductions effectively (old regime).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Negotiate structure: lower PF on full basic (if allowed), more
                  tax-efficient allowances.
                </li>
                <li>Claim HRA exemption correctly if you pay rent.</li>
              </ul>

              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-6">
                Disclaimer: This calculator is for educational purposes only.
                Tax laws, PF/ESI rules and professional tax slabs change over
                time and can vary by employer and location. Always consult your
                HR/payroll team or a qualified tax professional for personalised
                advice.
              </p>
